<h2>Typefaces</h2>

<div class="specimen">
	<h3 style="margin-top:0">Departure Mono — display, labels, code</h3>
	<p style="font-family:var(--font-display); font-size:var(--text-xl); margin-block:var(--space-2)">
		Symbols in a digital landscape
	</p>
	<p class="specimen-charset">
		ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz
		0123456789 ↑↓←→ ░▒▓█ ─│┌┐└┘ &amp;@#%*{}[]&lt;&gt;
	</p>
	<p>
		A pixel-grid monospace with a lo-fi technical character — quantitative
		without being arcade nostalgia. Single weight; hierarchy comes from
		size and space. OFL, by Helena Zhang / Toshi Omagari.
	</p>
</div>

<div class="specimen">
	<h3 style="margin-top:0">Space Grotesk — body prose</h3>
	<p>
		Body text is set in Space Grotesk, a grotesque derived from the
		monospaced Space Mono — its geometry is quantized at the skeleton even
		though its spacing is proportional. It exists so that essays remain
		effortless to read at length. To commit prose fully to the pixel grid
		instead, set <code>--font-body: var(--font-display)</code> in
		<code>tokens.css</code> — one token, entire site follows.
	</p>
</div>

<h2>Type scale</h2>

<p>Ratio 1.2 — distinction without drama, by decision.</p>

